## Authenticated API calls must never send empty Bearer tokens
- Never construct `Authorization: Bearer ${maybeToken}` with optional chaining (e.g. `session?.accessToken`) because it can produce `Bearer undefined` and trigger confusing "Invalid/expired token" errors.
- Always guard for a missing/expired token before calling protected endpoints; if missing, force re-auth (sign out / redirect) and skip the request.
- Prefer centralized auth header injection (e.g. Axios request interceptor) and centralized 401 handling to prevent scattered, inconsistent request code.

## NextAuth session objects can be partially defined
- Do not assume `session.user` exists even if `session` exists. Always use `session?.user?.<field>` (or explicit guards) in Client Components to prevent `undefined` property crashes in production.

## Never read or print secrets (.env, credentials)
- Do not read `.env`, `.env.*`, or any file that may contain secrets (keys/tokens/passwords) in chat output. Validate required env vars by checking presence/emptiness via code or targeted non-secret config files (like `.env.example`) instead.

## Secret hygiene: never patch `.env` in-agent
- Do not use file edits to write secrets into `.env` (patch diffs/tool inputs can leak). Prefer passing secrets via one-off process env vars when testing locally, and only document placeholders in `.env.example`.

## TiDB/MySQL DDL compatibility
- Avoid combining `ADD COLUMN` + `ADD CONSTRAINT` in a single `ALTER TABLE` statement. Split into separate `ALTER TABLE` statements to prevent TiDB DDL ordering/compat errors during migrations.

